  "script": "Phased arrays have evolved from World War Two radar to today's satellite links — let's trace that journey. Each element shifts its phase so waves add up in one direction and cancel everywhere else — pure electronics, no motors. Phased arrays now steer beams in military radar, five-G millimeter-wave base stations, and autonomous vehicle sensors. The XT-144 is a real hybrid X-band transmitter built for Taiwan's NSPO — one-forty-four antennas, sixty-four dBm EIRP, scanning sixty-five degrees. From wartime radar to LEO satellites, phased arrays follow one arc: semiconductors solved SWAP, hybrid wins where power is scarce."
}